Currently, you must manually extract the "concentration" and "viability" columns for analysis, which is time-consuming and error-prone.</p>
<h2><strong>What you want</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Directly analyze your initial, "raw" or "summary" sheet</strong>—where concentrations are in column headers and viability results (means, means % or otherwise) are in cells.</li>
<li><strong>Avoid copy-pasting</strong>: Script should extract the appropriate rows/columns automatically.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>How can we automate this?</strong></h2>
<p>Let's look at your image:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Concentration values</strong> are in columns <strong>2–13</strong> (yellow/green numbers).</li>
<li><strong>Viability %</strong> is in the colored cells, and the very last row (row "Mean Viability Extract") seems to be the summary you want to analyze.</li>
<li>The concentrations (x-axis) are the <strong>column headers</strong> (row 1, columns 2–13).</li>
<li>The "Mean Viability Extract" % is the value for each concentration.</li>
<li><strong>You want to fit the dose–response using those mean viability % values directly.</strong></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>Solution: Make a Script That Extracts Data Automatically</strong></h2>
<h3><strong>Option 1: Script Extracts Mean Viability Row and Column Headers</strong></h3>
<p><strong>Assumptions:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The concentrations are in a single row (e.g., row 1, columns 2+).</li>
<li>The "Mean Viability Extract" row is at a consistent position (e.g., "Mean Viability Extract" label in a certain column or row).</li>
<li>There may be other summary rows, so you want to select the correct one.</li>
</ul>
<h3><strong>Sample Script Logic</strong></h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Ask user to select the Excel file.</strong></li>
<li><strong>Read the sheet as data frame (not assuming specific column names).</strong></li>
<li><strong>Detect the "Mean Viability Extract" row and the concentration row.</strong></li>
<li><strong>Extract values, clean them, and run the analysis.</strong></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h3><strong>Would you like this script to:</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>Always use the <strong>first sheet</strong> and <strong>auto-detect</strong> the concentration and mean viability row?</li>
