<hr>
<h2><strong>1. Automatic Error &amp; Data Quality Checks</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Warn if any concentrations or viabilities are missing</strong> (NA).</li>
<li><strong>Flag outliers</strong> (e.g., points far from the fitted curve).</li>
<li><strong>Check for monotonicity:</strong> Some fits fail if the dose–response is too irregular.</li>
<li><strong>Log all files skipped due to missing keys/format issues.</strong></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>2. Results Summary Sheet</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>In the output Excel, create a <strong>summary sheet</strong> listing:
<ul>
<li>File name</li>
<li>Extract</li>
<li>IC50</li>
<li>SD</li>
<li>Key notes (e.g., warnings about fit/convergence)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Makes it easy to review all results at a glance.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>3. Choose Output Folder</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>Allow the user to <strong>specify an output folder</strong> rather than saving files in the working directory.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>4. Flexible Sheet Selection</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>Allow user to <strong>choose which sheet</strong> to process (if your files start having multiple plates/sheet).</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>5. Save R Workspace or Log</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>Optionally save an <code node="[object Object]">.RData</code> workspace or <code node="[object Object]">.Rds</code> file for each analysis for easy reproducibility.</li>
<li>Write a log file detailing all steps taken and any issues.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>6. IC50 Confidence Intervals</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>Output <strong>IC50 lower and upper confidence bounds</strong> (already available from <code node="[object Object]">ED()</code> but you can add to the Excel and plot).</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>7. Annotate Plot More</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>Optionally add:
<ul>
<li>The confidence interval for IC50 as a shaded band on the plot.</li>
<li>SD bars (error bars) on the data points.</li>
<li>Highlight outliers or points excluded from fit.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>8. Parallel Processing</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>If you process many files, you could use R's parallel packages (<code node="[object Object]">parallel</code>, <code node="[object Object]">future.apply</code>) to speed up multi-file processing.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>9. Export as PDF Report</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>Automatically generate a summary PDF for each file using <strong>R Markdown</strong> (great for sharing with collaborators).</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>10. Command Line/Script Arguments</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>So you can run the script <strong>unattended</strong> or in a pipeline, allow passing file paths and options as script arguments (<code node="[object Object]">commandArgs()</code>), not just interactively.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>11. Interactive Shiny App</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>For a user-friendly GUI, consider wrapping your analysis in a <strong>Shiny app</strong> for drag-and-drop analysis, immediate plot inspection, and download options.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>12. Advanced Curve Fitting Features</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>Optionally fit other models (e.g., 3-parameter, 5-parameter, biphasic).</li>
<li>Compare goodness-of-fit (AIC, R²) between models.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><strong>Sample: Add IC50 Confidence Interval to Output</strong></h2>
